Key Idea :  encrypt and decrypt will be called around 200 times for one new call, so, even if new is slow, if encrypt and decrypt are relatively fast, the whole process would be fast. 

Encrypt will have to remain O(N) because, we don't know which all words can be encrypted so we can not cache them prior to it's call.

Decrypt on the other hand returns how many Strings upon encryption in Dictionary will return that string. Since the dictionary is only initialized once, and has finite number of words with finite length, we can cache it's results in a hashmap. So, if we have the encrypted string as key, we can use that to get the count or return 0.

With some other minor optimizations, we can get the final Space and Time Complexities of the functions like so

new() -> TC : O(N<sup>2</sup>), SC : O(N)
Encrypt -> TC : O(N), SC : O(N)
Decrypt -> TC : O*(1), SC : O(1)

**Note that since we are using a HashMap, the time complexity can get to O(N), however, here since the number of words in dictionary isn't that much, it's O(1).**

