solutions.content:
Share two approaches:
- DFS + memo (top-down)
- DP (bottom-up)

#### DFS + memo
##### Steps
1. Track the `bal` to check if the path is valid
2. When `bal < 0`, prune it
3. If the `bal == 0` in the bottom-right corner, we find the valid path

use `memo` to enhance the performance.

##### Solution
- time complexity: `O(mn(m+n))`
- space complexity: `O(mn(m+n))`
```java
public boolean hasValidPath(char[][] grid) {
    int m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
    Boolean[][][] memo = new Boolean[m][n][m + n];
    return dfs(grid, 0, 0, 0, memo);
}

boolean dfs(char[][] grid, int i, int j, int bal, Boolean[][][] memo) {
    int m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
    if (i < 0 || i >= m || j < 0 || j >= n || bal < 0) return false;
    int cur = grid[i][j] == '(' ? 1 : -1;
    if (i == m - 1 && j == n - 1 && bal + cur == 0) return true;

    if (memo[i][j][bal] != null) return memo[i][j][bal];
    boolean valid = dfs(grid, i + 1, j, bal + cur, memo) || dfs(grid, i, j + 1, bal + cur, memo);

    if (valid) memo[i][j][bal] = true;
    else memo[i][j][bal] = false;
    return valid;
}
```
------
#### DP
##### Steps
1. For every `grid[i][j]`, we track all possible `bal` 
2. If the left or top of current grid has balance `bal`, then the current grid can have `bal +- 1` depends on the current grid is `(` or `)`
  Fomular is: 
  ```
  grid[i][j][bal] = grid[i-1][j][bal-cur] || grid[i][j-1][bal-cur] where cur = grid[i][j] == 1 ? 1 : 0
  ```
3. If the `bal < 0`, prune it
4. If the `bal == 0` in the bottom-right corner, we find the valid path

Note:
We can implement it use 2D set or 3D array to track the balance

##### Solution (2D Set)
- time complexity: `O(mn(m+n))`
- space complexity: `O(mn(m+n))`
```java
public boolean hasValidPath(char[][] grid) {
    int m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
    int[][] directions = new int[][]{{-1, 0}, {0, -1}};

    Set<Integer>[][] dp = new HashSet[m][n];
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            dp[i][j] = new HashSet<>();
        }
    }

    if (grid[0][0] == '(') dp[0][0].add(1);

    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            int cur = grid[i][j] == '(' ? 1 : -1;
            for (int[] d : directions) {
                int x = i + d[0], y = j + d[1];
                if (x < 0 || y < 0) continue;

                for (int bal : dp[x][y]) {
                    bal += cur;
                    if (bal < 0) continue;
                    dp[i][j].add(bal);
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return dp[m-1][n-1].contains(0);
}
```

##### Solution (3D Array)
```java
public boolean hasValidPath(char[][] grid) {
    int m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
    int[][] dirs = new int[][]{{-1, 0}, {0, -1}};
    boolean[][][] dp = new boolean[m][n][m + n + 1];


    if (grid[0][0] == '(') dp[0][0][1] = true;

    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            int cur = grid[i][j] == '(' ? 1 : -1;
            for (int bal = 0; bal < m + n; bal++) {
                if (i > 0 && bal - cur >= 0) {
                    dp[i][j][bal] |= dp[i - 1][j][bal - cur];
                }
                if (j > 0 && bal - cur >= 0) {
                    dp[i][j][bal] |= dp[i][j - 1][bal - cur];
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return dp[m-1][n-1][0];
}
```

