# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The idea here is simple..Just try all possible path !
But  trying all possible path using DFS **always** have repeated sub problem which results can be stored and used later when faced again!

The `is_visited `   is used to store whether we have visisted the cell with `open` number of open brackets. if it is true then we have vissited and the further journey will not give any valid parenthesis.


The dp combination is no.of.open brackets possible at any moment * i*j; 
`is_visited = new boolean[201][grid.length][grid[0].length];
`

Eg : is_visited[10][12][15] can be taken as When we have 5 open brackets reamining at grid[12][15] and is we have encountered the secenario or not ! ... if the is_visited[10][12][15] is `false` then we have to explore this path ..if not we have already explored and exploring the same path is unnecessary. 


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O( (m+n) * m * n) 
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O( (m+n) * m * n) 
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    boolean[][][] is_visited ;
    public boolean hasValidPath(char[][] grid) {
        if(grid[0][0] != '(' && grid[grid.length-1][grid[0].length-1] !=')') return false ;
        is_visited = new boolean[201][grid.length][grid[0].length];

        return algo(0 , 0 , grid ,0 );  
    }
    public boolean algo(int i , int j , char[][] grid , int open ){
        if( i>= grid.length || i< 0 || j>= grid[0].length || j<0) return false;

        if(grid[i][j] == '(') open++; 
        else open--;
        if( i== grid.length-1 && j== grid[0].length-1) {
            if(open != 0) return false ;
            return true;
        };

        if(open < 0 || is_visited[open][i][j] != false) return false;
        //right 
        if( algo(i+1 ,j ,grid , open)) return true;
        //down
        if(algo(i , j+1 , grid , open)) return true ;
        is_visited[open][i][j] = true;
        return false;

    }
}
```

