TL DR : **if at any point open < 0 then the path is not balanced**

**Q ) int dp[101][101][201] ? Why 201 ?**
A ) As the longest possible path from top left to bottom right is of (m+n-1) length.
(The path only ever moves down or right.)

Now, we have to go from the top left to bottom right by moving either down or right, the first point we get is to have a valid parantheses, the count of open = close, so if at any point the count of open < 0, then the path is not balanced and we return false.

Here the changing variables are i, j ( curr grid pos ) and the count of open and close brackets, it'll be much complex to consider anothet variable for closed brackets count so we add +1 to open when we see a '( ' & subtract -1 when we see a ')'.

from each position we can go either to the down (i+1, j) or right ( i, j+1), so we make 2 calls and we return true if either one of them returns true and assign it to dp[i][j][open].

If we somehow reach the bottom left, then we return true only when the count of open == 0 else we return false.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int dp[100][100][201];
    bool helper(vector<vector<char>>& grid, int i, int j, int open){
        if(i >= grid.size() || j >= grid[0].size()){
            return false;
        }

        if(grid[i][j] == '('){
            open++;
        }
        else{
            open--;
        }
        if(open < 0){
            return false;
        }
        if(dp[i][j][open] != -1){
            return dp[i][j][open];
        }
        if(i == grid.size() - 1 && j == grid[0].size() - 1){
            if(open == 0){
                return true;
            }
            else{
                return false;
            }
        }
        int next = helper(grid, i+1, j, open) || helper(grid, i, j+1, open);
        return dp[i][j][open] = next;
    }


    bool hasValidPath(vector<vector<char>>& grid) {
        if(grid[0][0] == ')'){
            return false;
        }
        memset(dp, -1, sizeof(dp));
        bool ans = helper(grid, 0, 0, 0);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

