> **Update on 09/08/2022: C++ BFS solution added**
> 
#### Foreword
I saw a lot of solutions with `O(MN*log(MN))`, but we can do better than that. 
Here I am providing 2 solutions. I think solution 2 may be more straightforward.
Both solutions run in `O(MN)`.

#### Solution 1 (Java) - BFS + DFS
Let's slowly expand the reachable areas with BFS eliminating walls and then explore with DFS.

- Perform a BFS with each BFS layer with a counter (num of elimination required).

- Within each BFS, we perform a DFS from each cell in the BFS queue.
- Within each DFS, we explore all the cells and enqueue all the walls we can reach back into the BFS queue.
- If we are able to reach the end and it is not a wall, we return the current counter.
- If not, then we do BFS again and destroy all the walls enqueued in step 1 by marking it as 0
- Remember to mark all the cells we've visited as seen to avoid infinite loop.

The time complexity of this BFS + DFS approach is O(MN) because each cell is only explored at most 2 times. 
`Time O(MN)`
`Space O(MN)`
```Java
class Solution {
    int m, n;
    public int minimumObstacles(int[][] grid) {
        m = grid.length; n = grid[0].length;
        Queue<int[]> queue = new ArrayDeque<>();
        queue.offer(new int[]{0, 0});
        for (int i = 0; ; i++){ // i = num of elimination required.
            for (int j = queue.size(); j > 0; j--){
                int[] p = queue.poll();
                grid[p[0]][p[1]] = 0; // eliminate this wall, mark it as 0
                if (explore(p[0], p[1], grid, queue))
                    return i;
            }
        }
    }

    private boolean explore(int i, int j, int[][] grid, Queue<int[]> queue){
        if (i < 0 || j < 0 || i == m || j == n || grid[i][j] < 0)
            return false;
        if (grid[i][j] == 1){
            grid[i][j] = -1; // mark as seen so it doesn't get enqueued again
            queue.add(new int[]{i, j});
            return false;
        }
        if (i+j == n+m-2)
            return true;
        grid[i][j] = -1;
        return explore(i + 1, j, grid, queue)
            || explore(i - 1, j, grid, queue)
            || explore(i, j + 1, grid, queue)
            || explore(i, j - 1, grid, queue);
    }
}
```

#### Solution 2 (C++) - BFS
I was reviewing problem and now I found it more straight forward to just do BFS. 
I have since switched from being a Java user to C++, hence the below.

The idea is more or less the same, but this time we mark it inside BFS. 
More details can be found in the comments below.

`Time O(MN)`
`Space O(MN)`
```C++
    int minimumObstacles(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int m = size(grid), n = size(grid[0]);
        queue<pair<int,int>> q, nq;
        vector<vector<bool>> seen(m, vector<bool>(n));
        seen[0][0] = 1;
        q.push({0, 0});
        int dx[4]{0, 0, -1, 1};
        int dy[4]{1, -1, 0, 0};
        for (int i = 0; ;++i){
            while(!q.empty()){ // q is the current queue
                auto [x, y] = q.front();
                if (x+y==m+n-2){
                    return i;
                }
                q.pop();
                for (int k = 0; k < 4; ++k){ // explore all 4 directions
                    int nx = x + dx[k];
                    int ny = y + dy[k];
                    if (nx < 0 || ny < 0 || nx == m || ny == n || seen[nx][ny]){
                        continue;
                    }
                    if (grid[nx][ny]){ // if it is an obstacle, put it in for the next queue
                        nq.push({nx, ny});
                    }else{ // otherwise it is for the current queue
                        q.push({nx, ny});
                    }
                    seen[nx][ny] = 1; // mark it seen in both cases
                }
            }
            swap(q, nq);
        }
    }
```

