solutions.content:
**DFS *(Accecpted)***
**Note -** for example like `[[0, 1], [0, 1]]` in this case `(1, 1)` cell visit twice, 1st time from `(0, 1)` cell with cost `2` and 2nd time from `(1, 0)` cell with cost `1` even though `1` is better, queue contains both. Meanwhile `dp` got updated at time of `enqueue`, so the `savior` condition will not allow those expensive paths.

**for CPP users avoid using vector**

*Time complexity :* `greater than O(H * W)` cause a cell can be visited more than once, or it might be `O(V + E)` ≈ `O(H * (W - 1)) + O(W * (H - 1))` 
where  `H = grid.size(), W = grid[0].size(), V = no. of vertices, E = no. of edges`
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumObstacles(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        const auto INF = int(1e5) + 5;
        const vector<pair<int, int>> DIR = {{0, 1}, {0, -1}, {1, 0}, {-1, 0}};
        int H = (int) grid.size(), W = (int) grid[0].size();
        // vector<vector<int>> dp(H, vector<int> (W, INF));
        int dp[H][W];

        for (int i = 0; i < H; i++)
            for (int j = 0; j < W; j++)
                dp[i][j] = INF;

        queue<tuple<int, int, int>> q;
        q.push(make_tuple(0, 0, grid[0][0]));

        while (!q.empty()) {
            for (int i = q.size(); i > 0; i--) {
                auto [r, c, cost] = q.front();
                q.pop();

                if (r == H - 1 && c == W - 1) {
                    ans = min(ans, cost);
                    continue;
                }

                if (dp[r][c] < cost)  // saved me from getting TLE
                    continue;

                for (auto [x, y] : DIR) 
                    if (r + x >= 0 && c + y >= 0 && r + x < H && c + y < W) 
                        if (cost + grid[r + x][c + y] < dp[r + x][c + y]) {
                            dp[r + x][c + y] = cost + grid[r + x][c + y];
                            q.push(make_tuple(r + x, c + y, cost + grid[r + x][c + y]));
                        }
