# Intuition
The goal of this problem is for us to travel from the cell (0,0) in the matrix to cell (n-1,m-1) n=number of rows m=number of columns and we have to choose such path where we need to remove either 0 or the minimum breakers that some cell might have.

# Approach
The approach that comes to mind seeing this grid problem is of dynamic programming but having tried that and getting WA gave an intuition  that we cannot assume that a path that is optimal for now will remain optimal for the rest of the traversal.

So the problems that led to take a deque instead of queue as the data structure of choice was we have to take both an empty cell and a cell with blockers because maybe the cell that is empty is trying to trick us and when we go further inside the matrix we might see we had one blocker to remove above if we haven't chosen the empty cell now we have 3.

So we need to add both empty cell and blocker cell now there is a matter of preference that we should consider too.
We have to take the empty cell whenever necessary if it doesn't provide the optimal answer go for the blocker.
Thus the birth of deque.

Now take another matrix that will store the answer of every path we are going to traverse and give us the answer at the cell (n-1)(m-1).

While using bfs we see whenever we find a empty cell we push it in front and blocker at the back.
Go on traversing till the deque is not empty.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O((n*m)log(n*m));

- Space complexity:O(n*m)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumObstacles(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
       vector<pair<int,int>> directions={{-1,0},{1,0},{0,1},{0,-1}};
       int n=grid.size();
       int m=grid[0].size();
      vector<vector<int>> dp(n,vector<int>(m,INT_MAX));
      vector<vector<int>> visited(n,vector<int>(m,0));
      deque<pair<int,int>> q;
      q.push_front({0,0});
      visited[0][0]=1;
      dp[0][0]=0;
      while(!q.empty()){
        auto curr=q.front();
        q.pop_front();
        for(auto direct:directions){
          int rrow=curr.first+direct.first;
          int ccol=curr.second+direct.second;
          if(rrow>=0 and rrow<n and ccol>=0 and ccol<m){
            if(!visited[rrow][ccol]){
              visited[rrow][ccol]=1;
              dp[rrow][ccol]=dp[curr.first][curr.second]+(grid[rrow][ccol]==1);
              if(grid[rrow][ccol]==1){
                q.push_back({rrow,ccol});
              }else q.push_front({rrow,ccol});
            }
          }
        }
      }
      return dp[n-1][m-1];
    }
};
```

