# Intuition
find all routes from src to dest 
count all the obstacles along the way
route having min number of obstacles + ( shortest one) along the way should be the best one?
think about - minimum number of obstacles to remove 
?dijkstra - consider obstacle path as cost to be paid 
0 - path with no cost
1 - path with 1 cost
Add the obstacle removal cost to distance 
Dijkstra - use PQ 


# Complexity
**- Time complexity:**
Initializing the dist array with Integer.MAX_VALUE takes O(m * n), where m is the number of rows and n is the number of columns in the grid.
The PriorityQueue (pq) can have at most m * n elements, and in the worst case, all cells are processed, so the loop will run a maximum of m * n times.
Inside the loop, you have a loop that iterates over the four directions, which is a constant factor.
Overall, the time complexity of the code is **O(m * n + log(m * n))**, where log(m * n) comes from the PriorityQueue operations.
**- Space complexity:**
O(m * n) 
# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minimumObstacles(int[][] grid) {
        int m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
        int[][] dirs = {{0,1},{1,0},{0, -1}, {-1, 0}};
        // to capture the distance
        int[][] dist = new int[m][n];
        // initially populate the distance with Infinity
        for(int[]arr: dist) Arrays.fill(arr, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        // Create PQ to hold grid positions and their distances
        // PQ will store {x, y, dist} as triplets sorted by dist asc 
        Queue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> a[2] - b[2]);
        // add starting position to the queue which is upper left cornter
        // (0,0) with distance set to zero
        pq.offer(new int[]{0, 0, 0});
        dist[0][0] = 0;
        while(!pq.isEmpty()){
            int[] current = pq.poll(); // poll the one with smallest distance
            int x = current[0];
            int y = current[1];
            int distance = current[2];
            // check if we have reached destination
            if(x == m-1 && y==n-1) return distance;
            // now from current cell move in all 4 directions
            // below for loop creates new coordinates of the cell
            for(int[]dir: dirs) {
                int nx = x + dir[0]; //new x
                int ny = y + dir[1]; //new y
                //validate out of grid coordinates and reject them
                if(nx<0 || nx>=m || ny<0 || ny>=n) continue;
                //for valid coordinates re-compute the distance from previous source i.e {x, y}
                if(dist[nx][ny]> distance + grid[nx][ny]) {
                    dist[nx][ny] = distance + grid[nx][ny];
                    pq.offer(new int[]{nx, ny, dist[nx][ny]});
                }
            }

        }

        // dist[][] will contain the cost of reaching to m-1, n-1
        return dist[m-1][n-1];
    }
}
```

