# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
que looks like shortest path type. que can be solved using dijkstra with small variation.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. here we will have a 2-D arr and v[r][c] -> no of obstacle removed to reach the {r,c}.in original dijkstra v[r][c] ->  shortest distance to reach {r,c}. (we can use dijkstra algo). 
2. in priority_queue we will store {v[r][c],{r,c}}.
remember in original dijkstra we store the {distnace,node} but in matrix node is nothing but {r,c}.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n*m*log(n*m))

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n*m)

