  eg. ["coffee","donuts","time","toffee"]

 => **Create an array of list and store according to first char after removing the first char**
```
*   arr[2] = { offee } // represents c
*   arr[3] = { onuts } // represents d
*   arr[19] = { ime, offee } //represents t
```

 => **now apply the HashSet part operation**
  ```
set.addAll(arr[i]);
set.addAll(arr[j]);

  ```
For every possible pair of distinct characters the number of distinct names are : 
**`disName += 2 * (arr[i].size() - set.size()) * (arr[j].size() - set.size());`**

* `(arr[i].size() - set.size())` - number of distinct strings that are present for second character but not in first character
* `(arr[j].size() - set.size())` - number of distinct strings that are present for first character but not in second character

##### Code : 
 ```
class Solution {
        public long distinctNames(String[] ideas) {
        List<String> arr[] = new ArrayList[26];               // create array of ArrayList
        long disName = 0;                                     // Instead ArrayList, HashSet can be used
        for(int i = 0; i < 26; i++)                           // assign new ArrayList to each index
            arr[i] = new ArrayList<>();

        for(String s : ideas)
            arr[s.charAt(0) - 'a'].add(s.substring(1));       // store each string A/C to its 1st char

        for(int i = 0; i < 25; i++) {
            for(int j = i + 1; j < 26; j++) {
                Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();            // store all strings of arr[i] & arr[j]

                set.addAll(arr[i]);
                set.addAll(arr[j]);
                disName += (arr[i].size() - set.size()) * (arr[j].size() - set.size());     // no. of pairs possible
            }
        }

        return disName * 2;
    }
}
```

