# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Swap the first letters of ideaA and ideaB with each other.
There are only 26 alphabets in English we can we make use of this.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(n*26*26)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long distinctNames(vector<string>& ideas) {
        unordered_map<char,set<string>> mp; //creating a unordered_map w[0] as key and w[1 to n] as value stored in a set.
        for(int i=0;i<ideas.size();i++){
            mp[ideas[i][0]].insert(ideas[i].substr(1));
        } 
        long long ans =0,samesuffix=0;
        for(int i =97;i<122;i++){          //iterating through 26 alphabets
            for(int j=i+1;j<123;j++){
                samesuffix=0;
                for(auto it3:mp[i]){   // checking if 2 map value set words have same w[1 to n ]
                    if( mp[j].find(it3) !=  mp[j].end() ) 
                        samesuffix++;   // incrementing samesuffix
                }
                ans += 2*( mp[i].size()-samesuffix)*(mp[j].size()-samesuffix); //updating the ans by removing the samesuffix words .
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```

