# Intuition
The brute force approach for this problem will be to check every pair for the given situation that wether the any of the strings already exits in the array after swaping their first letter.

This approach will be of O(n^2) time complexity and O(n) space complexity for storing a hashmap of the ideas.

->We can optimize it by not checking for pairs which have common prefix (first letter) and common suffix (i.e. rest of the string expect the first letter).

We can use this optimization to create another approach that will be of better time complexity.

# Approach
In this approach we will create a unordered map with the prefix as the key and a set of suffixes will the value of the key.
As in the first test case the map look something like this:-
{
c : (offee),
d : (onuts),
t : (ime,offee)
}
In the worst case there will be 26 entries(sets) in the map.
Now we only have to compare sets with different prefixes because words with common prefix do not satisfy the condition of the problem.
For example (time and toffee) will never satisfy the situation.

Now we will compare every set with another set. To do so we will run a loop from a to z.

We also have to for common suffixes in a set because they also do not satisfy the situation.

We can find the number of name that can be made form a set by this formula:-
names=2*(number of elements in 1st set - number of mutual suffixes)*(number of elements in 2nd set - number of mutual suffixes)
2 because each pair will make 2 names.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:  O(n*m)
1. Where m is the average number of elements in a stack and n is the number of elements in the arrray.

- Space complexity: O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:

    long long distinctNames(vector<string>& ideas) {
        //unordered map and set because finding an element will be  of O(1)
        unordered_map<char,unordered_set<string>> m;
        long long res=0;
        //creating the map with 1st letter as key and the rest will be in the set 
        for (auto idea:ideas) m[idea[0]].insert(idea.substr(1));
        for(char i='a';i<'z';i++){ //this loop will run from a to y 
            for(char j=i+1;j<='z';j++){
                int mutual=0;
                for(auto x:m[i]){//checking for mutual elements in the pair of sets
                    if(m[j].find(x)!=m[j].end()) mutual++;
                }
                res+=2*(m[i].size()-mutual)*(m[j].size()-mutual);
            }
        }

        return res;
    }
};
```

