solutions.content:
I was surprised to see that there are ony few bitmasking related solutions(maybe using bitmasks to improve runtime in these kinds of problems are not very popular) in the dicuss section, hence I'm posting mine.

**Solution Idea**:
1. we have 2 hashmaps, one for storing `suffix -> mask` and another for storing `suffix -> group` where, `suffix` is the substring `ai[1..n - 1]` for any string `ai` in ideas, group is a set of strings having the same `suffix`, and `mask` represents the bitmask of characters present as starting letters in any string of a group.
2. we have another matrix 26 x 26 matrix `cnt`, where at any point of time `cnt[x][y]` represents the number of strings which we have seen so far having `x` as a starting letter and doesn't have any string with `y` as a starting letter in its `group`   
3. traverse the strings group by group at a time and for each string in any group count the total number of strings in the previous groups it can pair with, this can be found by adding `cnt[x][y]` to answer where x can be any character which is not in current group's bitmask and y is the `ai[0]`(starting letter of current string)
4. update the `cnt` matrix by again traversing the current group. For each character `x` which is not present in the current group's bitmask do, `cnt[y][x]++` where `y` is the starting letter of the current string `ai`. By doing this we are saying that "ok, we have a string with staring letter `x` which can be grouped with any string with `y` as a starting letter in the future.
5. return `2 * ans` because if we can make a pair (ai, aj), we can also make a pair (aj, ai)

**Code:**
```
	long long distinctNames(vector<string>& ideas) {
      unordered_map<string, int> masks;
      unordered_map<string, vector<string>> groups;

      for (auto &ai: ideas) {
        string suff = ai.substr(1);
        groups[suff].push_back(ai);
        masks[suff] |= 1 << (ai[0] - 'a');
      }

      long long ans = 0;
      int cnt[26][26] = {};
      for (auto &[suff, group]: groups) {
        int curr_mask = masks[suff];
        for (auto &ai: group) {
          for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
            if (curr_mask & (1 << i)) continue;
            ans += cnt[i][ai[0] - 'a'];
          }
        }

        for (auto &ai: group) {
          for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
            if (curr_mask & (1 << i)) continue;
            cnt[ai[0] - 'a'][i]++;
          }
        }
      }

      return 2 * ans;
    }
```

**Complexity Analysis**:
*Time Complexity*: 

The preprocessing step takes `O(9*N)` time (because we are iterating over all strings and for each string we're processing the `suffix[1..n - 1]` of that string which can have length of at most 9.
```
for (auto &ai: ideas) {
	string suff = ai.substr(1);
	groups[suff].push_back(ai);
	masks[suff] |= 1 << (ai[0] - 'a');
}
```

Then we're traversing each group, that's `O(N)`
```
for (auto &[suff, group]: groups) {
	...
}
```

and in each group, we're doing 3 things

first, we're getting the current mask using the suffix of the group, that's `O(L = 9)`, where L is the maximum length of the suffix
```
for (auto &[suff, group]: groups) {
	int curr_mask = masks[suff];
	...
}
```

next, for each string in the current group, we have a loop that runs 26 times and inside that we've a bitwise operation, that's `O(26)` (note that I'm considering the cost of the bitwise operation as `O(1)` here, although some people will argue it's `O(log2(26))`. For more details on this topic refer [Time complexity of bitwise operators in C++](https://leetcode.com/discuss/general-discussion/375033/bitwise-operators-complexity/338350))
```
for (auto &[suff, group]: groups) {
	...
	for (auto &ai: group) {
		for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
			if (curr_mask & (1 << i)) continue;
			ans += cnt[i][ai[0] - 'a'];
  }
}
```

then at last we have a loop that runs 26 times for each string in the current group and update the `cnt` matrix, that's `O(26)` again
```
for (auto &[suff, group]: groups) {
	...
	for (auto &ai: group) {
		for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
			if (curr_mask & (1 << i)) continue;
			cnt[ai[0] - 'a'][i]++;
		}
	}
}
```
summing up, we have `O(9 * N + N * (9 + 26 + 26))` = `O(9 * N + 61 * N)`
which is `O(61 * N)`

*Space Complexity*: 
we are using 2 hashmaps and one can have upto `n` strings with each string having a maximum length of 10. Hence, the space complexity would be `O(10 * N)`

This solution actually has a good runtime but it could be improved a bit by some more preprocessing and removing redundant code
