solutions.content:
The code below works by grouping all passed words by their first character, where each letter-group contains the words' strings without their first letter (i.e. the "suffix" of the word which is the string from the second letter to the end of the word).  The groups are implemented by an array of 26 HashSets, where the HashSets contain the suffixes of their group's words.  The total number of combinations of valid company names will be the sum the valid combinations from all possible pairs of groups.  If n is the number of suffix strings in common between two groups, then the number of valid company names that can be formed with any pair of groups, will be the size of the first group minus n, times the size of the second group minus n.

After the words are grouped into the 26 HashSets, if some letters are not used as a first letter in any word, that letter-group's HashSet will be empty, so we squeeze out all empty HashSets.  Two later sections of code will compare all possible pairs of HashSets, which could result in 26\*26 comparisons to get the total number of valid company names.  By squeezing out empty group's HashSets the number of group HashSet comparisons can be reduced.  For example, if only 5 different letters are used as first letters of the passed words, then only 5\*5 HashSet comparisons will be needed.  We can further reduce the number of group comparisons by only comparing the groups in one direction.  For example, given groups A and B, the number of company names formed by the pair of groups A,B will be the same number as reversing the direction to B,A, so we only count one direction of comparison, then multiply by 2.  Also, don't compare any group with itself, because there will be no valid company names.

The code then uses a 2-D array to calculate the number of suffixes in common between all possible group HashSet pairs, i.e. the number of suffixes in the intersection of the pair of HashSets.  After the number of all HashSet pair's common (intersecting) suffixes have been calculated, then the number of valid company name combinations for each pair of groups is calculated and summed.

This code ran as fast as 93ms in August 2023.

If useful, then please upvote.

### --- Commented Code ---
```
class Solution {
    public long distinctNames(String[] ideas) {
        // Add all words (from second character on) into an array of HashSet's, 
        // indexed by the first letter of the words.  One HashSet for each 
        // possible first letter of the words.  Group the words by the first 
        // letter of the words, and each group contains the suffix of the 
        // words (i.e. each group contains the words' strings from the second 
        // letter of the word until the end of the word).
        HashSet<String>[] sets = new HashSet[26];
        for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++)  sets[i] = new HashSet();
        for (String s : ideas)  sets[s.charAt(0) - 'a'].add(s.substring(1));

        // Remove HashSet's that don't have any words in them.
        int inn = 0;
        while (inn < 26 && sets[inn].size() != 0)  inn++;   // Find first empty HashSet, if any.
        int used = inn;
        while (inn < 26) {          // Loop to remove empty HashSet's.
            if (sets[inn].size() != 0) 
                sets[used++] = sets[inn];
            inn++;
        }
        if (used <= 1)  return 0;   // If only one non-empty HashSet, then no valid company names.

        // Find the number of words in the intersection of all possible pair 
        // combinations from the Array of HashSets.
        int[][] intersectionSizes = new int[used][used];
        for (int i = used - 2; i >= 0; i--) {       // Loop through first HashSet's of the pairs.
            int[] intersectRow = intersectionSizes[i];
            for (String suffix : sets[i])           // Loop to test first HashSet strings for intersection.
                for (int j = used - 1; j > i; j--)  // Loop through second HashSet's of the pairs. 
                    if (sets[j].contains(suffix))   // If string in both HashSets of pair
                        intersectRow[j]++;
        }

        // Add up the combinations from all possible pairs of HashSet's, without including the 
        // intersection suffix strings between the pair of HashSet's.
        long count = 0;
        for (int i = used - 2; i >= 0; i--) {       // Loop through first HashSet's of the pairs.
            int iSize = sets[i].size();
            for (int j = used - 1; j > i; j--)      // Loop through second HashSet's of the pairs. 
                count += (iSize - intersectionSizes[i][j]) * (sets[j].size() - intersectionSizes[i][j]);
        }                                           // Add number of company names from pair of HashSet's.

        // Return the count of valid company names.  The "*2" is because each 
        // pair of valid company names can swap the order of the words and 
        // still be a valid company name.
        return count * 2;
    }
}
