solutions.content:
**Explanation**
For each bit position (0 to 31), we count the number of 1 bits for all elements in the nums array.
We store this in bitCounts.

Now, if we take the XOR of the entire array. In the XOR output, the bits at the positions for which the bit count is even will be 0 and for which the bit count is odd will be 1.

If we could somehow perform the operation to change the even bit counts into odd ones, we would get the maximum XOR output.

We can do that.
For a number, we can perform the operation such that a 1 bit becomes 0.
**Note: we can select any non-negative integer x, i.e. x does not have to be from within the array.**

So we can make any 1 bit 0, but we can't make a 0 bit 1.
We cannot set a 0 bit to 1 using the operation as we are taking the bitwise AND with nums[i].

We can always select such an x that we can change any 1 bit to 0.

Hence, for every bit position in the bit count which has a non-zero value, we can have that bit to be 1 in the answer. For the positions for which the bit count is 0, those bits in the answer will be 0.


**Method 1.1: finding the bit counts for every bit position and then computing the answer**
Check Method 1.2 for O(1) Space.
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumXOR(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<int> bitCounts(32, 0);

        for (int& num : nums) {
            for (int i = 0; i < 32; i++) {
                // Increment bitCounts[i] if the (i)th bit of nums is 1
                bitCounts[i] += (num >> i) & 1;
            }
        }

        // Compute the answer from the bit counts as given in the explanation.
        int ans = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < 32; i++) {
            if (bitCounts[i] > 0) {
                ans += pow(2, i); // you could probably do some bit manipulation here instead of 
                                  // using pow, but that's when I got the inspiration for 
                                  // Method 1.2
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```


**Method 1.2: just take the bitwise OR of all numbers to get the answer**
In the answer, we want all bits with non-zero bit counts to be 1 and the remaining bits to be 0. We can compute this answer by taking the bitwise OR of all the elements in the array.
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumXOR(vector<int>& nums) {
        int ans = 0;

        for (int& num : nums) {
            ans |= num;
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```

