Observe that **a&(a^x) = (a&a)^(a&x) = a^(a&x)**
Observe that **(a&x)** will be set only on those bits which is already 1.
ie. if a has a binary representation of 

a = 100011
then a&x can be 100001, 100010, 100011, 000011, 000010, 000001, 000000.

Now the XOR of this A&X will make those bits off which is present in (a&x), 
thus we can set X accordingly and set any bit of A as off.

Now for maximum XOR of array, we need to look bitwise at each position and check if there is atleast one number which has this bit on, if yes, then we can make this bit on in the answer(by switching off all bits in rest of array at this position) else we can't.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumXOR(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int num = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<32;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                int x = (nums[j]>>i);
                if(x%2) {num += (1<<i); break;}
            }
        }
        return num;
    }
};
```

