if we consider ```ith``` bit of numbers then we can notice that 
* if the number of set bits are odd then ```XOR``` of that position will be ```1```.
* if the number of set bits are even then ```XOR``` of that position will be ```0```.

we know that taking ```and``` of a number with any other number can never increase the given number.
i.e. ```result``` of  ```x & y``` will always be ```<= x```  no matter what the value of ```y``` is.

* if we want to maximize our ```result``` then we want to have maximum number of set bits possible in our answer.
* now, if the number of set bits at a position is ```odd``` which is what we want then we set the corresponding bit to ```1``` in the answer.
* if the corresponding number of set bits is ```even``` then we want to flip one bit of any number to make the count of set bits ```odd``` at that position.

```
class Solution {
    public int maximumXOR(int[] nums) {
	    int answer = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < 31; i++) {
            int bits = 0;
            int mask = (1 << i);
            for (int n : nums) {
                if ((mask & n) > 0) {
                    bits++;
                }
            }
            if (bits > 0) {
			    //  we could flip any ith bit in any nuber and make the xor 1
				//  but we can not set an odd bit 
                answer |= (1 << i);
            }
        }
        return answer;
    }
}

