# Intuition
What does a&(a^b) do?
It says that whatever bit of a is different from that of b, keep it. Turn all other bits to 0.

Those different bits will anyway produce 1 when XORed. 

The bits that were same as that of b are now 0. These bits were either 0 or 1 in b. If they were 1, they are now 0, and will produce 1 when XORed. 

Repeating the same operation on a again with b as x shall cause no change in a.


Also please note that bits that are 0 in both a and b will never tranform to 1 with any number of operation between a nd b.

Hence the intuition. 


