# Intuition
As we may choose arbitrary `x`, the term `t = (nums[i] XOR x)` can result arbitrary numbers by choosing `x = (nums[i] XOR t)`. As an `AND` operation is applied to `nums[i]` and `t`, arbitrary bits can be set to 0, but a 0 bit in `nums[i]` can not be set to 1. Therefore, for each position where at least one 1 bit in `nums` exists, all but one 1 can be set to 0. Therefore, the result equals the `OR` operation applied to all elements of `nums`.

# Approach
Iterating over the array and applying the `OR` operator to all elements.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(n)$$

- Space complexity:
$$O(1)$$ additional space

