# Intuition
Start with an example
```
nums = [ 3, 2, 4, 6 ]
3 = 0011
2 = 0010
4 = 0100
6 = 0110
XOR(3, 2, 4, 6) = 0011

we have zero 1s at index 0 -> XOR of all bits at index 0 becomes 0
we have two 1s at index 1 -> XOR of all bits at index 1 becomes 0
we have three 1s at index 2 -> XOR of all bits at index 2 becomes 1
we have one 1s at index 3 -> XOR of all bits at index 3 becomes 1
...
we have Odd 1s at index i -> XOR of all bits at index i becomes 1 (good)
we have Even 1s at index i -> XOR of all bits at index i becomes 0 (not good)
```

The given operation `nums[i] = nums[i] & (nums[i] ^ x)` let us to **clear any single bit of** `nums[i]` if we want to.

Therefore, if we want to **maximize** the result of *XOR*(`nums`), we can apply a operation to **reduce an even number of 1s to an odd number of 1s** to get a **1** at that resultant bit.

Be aware of zero 1s, zero is an even number but we are not able to reduce it to get an odd number of 1s.
